| ''[[Ugly Betty]]'' || Cal Hartley || 10 episode\n|-\n|2010 || ''[[The Electric Company]]'' || The Ronald || Episode: The Great Compromise\n|-\n|2010 || ''[[Rubicon]]'' || James Wheeler || 7 episodes\n|-\n|2011 || ''[[Are We There Yet? (TV series)|Are We There Yet?]]'' || Thunder Clark || Episode: She Got Game\n|-\n|2011 || ''[[Royal Pains]]'' || Charles Woodward || Episode: Rash Talk\n|-\n|2011 || ''[[Bored to Death]]'' || Bernard || 6 episodes\n|-\n|2014 || ''[[Black Box (TV series)|Black Box]]'' || Hunter Black || 2 episodes\n|-\n|2016 || ''Understudies'' || Clement Shaw || Episode: Table Manners\n|-\n|2016 || ''[[Madam Secretary (TV series)|Madam Secretary]]'' || Amb. Arlen Maxwell || Episode: The Middle Way\n|-\n|2015-16 || ''[[Impastor]]'' || Alden Schmidt || 20 episodes\n|-\n|2013-17 || ''[[Veep]]'' || Jim Marwood || 8 episodes\n|-\n|2018-19 || ''[[Succession (TV series)|Succession]]'' || Karl || 12 episodes\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Theatre ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\" | Venue \n|-\n|1977 || ''[[The Shadow Box]]'' || Mark || [[Morosco Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1980 || ''[[Lunch Hour]]'' || Peter || [[Ethel Barrymore Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1988 || ''[[Speed-the-Plow]]'' || Bobby Gould || [[Bernard B. Jacobs Theatre|Royale Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|1988 || ''Getting and Spending'' || Richard O'Neill || [[Helen Hayes Theatre]], Broadway\n|-\n|2004 || ''Five by Tenn'' || Performer || rowspan=2|[[Manhattan Theatre Club]], Broadway\n|-\n|2005 || ''Moonlight and Magnolias'' || Victor Fleming \n|-\n|2006 || ''Lovely Day'' || Performer || [[Samuel Beckett|Samuel Beckett Theatre]], New York\n|-\n|2006 || ''Elvis and Juliet'' || Joey Francis Lesley || [[June Havoc|June Havoc Theatre]], New York\n|-\n|2007-07 || ''Regrets Only'' || Jack McCullough || [[Manhattan Theatre Club]], Broadway \n|-\n|2008 || ''[[The Seagull]]'' || Yevgeny Sergeyevich Dorn || [[Classic Stage Company]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|2008 || ''[[To be, or not to be]]'' || Josef Tura || [[Manhattan Theatre Club]], Broadway\n|-\n|2012 || ''Warrior Class'' || Nathan || [[Second Stage Theatre]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|2013 || ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]'' || Grandpa Hoover || [[Second Stage Theatre]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|2014 || ''[[The Country House (play)|The Country House]]'' || Walter Keegan || [[Manhattan Theatre Club]], Broadway\n|-\n|2017 || ''[[The Skin of Our Teeth]]'' || Mr. Antroubus || Polonsky Shakespeare Center, Brooklyn\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|711058|David Rasche}}\n* {{amg name|id=58851|name=David Rasche}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|4840}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rasche, David}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Belleville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1944|8|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Belleville, Illinois|Belleville]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  = {{ubl|[[Elmhurst College]]|[[University of Chicago]]}}\n| occupation  = Actor\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Heather Lupton|1980}}\n| children    = 3\n| yearsactive = 1977\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''David Rasche''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|\u00e6|\u0283|i\u02d0}} {{Respell|RASH|ee|}})<ref>{{cite web|title=Say How?|url=https://www.loc.gov/nls/about/organization/standards-guidelines/qrst/#r|website=National Library Service for the Blind and Physically Handicapped|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> (born August 7, 1944) is an [[Americans|American]] theater, film and television actor who is best known for his portrayal of the title character in the 1980s satirical police sitcom ''[[Sledge Hammer!]]''  Since then he has often played characters in positions of authority, in both serious and comical turns. In television he is known for his recurring performances in ''[[L.A. Law]]'', ''[[Monk (TV series)|Monk]]'', ''[[The West Wing]]'', ''[[Veep]]'', and ''[[Succession (TV series)|Succession]]''.  \n\n==Early life==\nRasche was born in [[Belleville, Illinois|Belleville]], [[Illinois]] (less than {{convert|20|mi|abbr=on}} from [[St. Louis, Missouri]]<ref name=Belleville-StL>{{cite web| url= https://www.google.com/maps/dir/St.+Louis,+MO/Belleville,+IL/@38.5707123,-90.1590213,12z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m13!4m12!1m5!1m1!1s0x87d8b4a9faed8ef9:0xbe39eaca22bbe05b!2m2!1d-90.1994042!2d38.6270025!1m5!1m1!1s0x87d8a9d45ea93095:0x3e5bad413dc569f1!2m2!1d-89.9839935!2d38.5200504| publisher= Google Maps| title= St. Louis, MO to Belleville, IL| access-date= March 16, 2017}}</ref>). His father was a [[minister (Christianity)|minister]] and farmer.<ref name= Elmhurst>{{cite journal |url=http://www.elmhurst.edu/magazine/alumnistories/7718072.html |title=David Rasche '66, star of stage, screen and sit-com, is a celebrated 'smart performer' |first=Laura |last=Shin |journal=Prospect Magazine |publisher=[[Elmhurst College]] |accessdate=January 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202064538/http://www.elmhurst.edu/magazine/alumnistories/7718072.html |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nRasche graduated from [[Elmhurst College]] in 1966; his grandfather was also an alumnus.<ref name= Elmhurst /> Coming from \"a long line of Evangelical and United Church of Christ ministers\", he attended the [[University of Chicago Divinity School]] for two years, then quit. He did, however, receive a graduate degree in English from [[University of Chicago]].<ref name= figuring />\n\nHe studied acting under [[Sanford Meisner]].<ref name= figuring />\n\n==Career==\n===Early years===\nHe worked as a writer and teacher, including teaching English for two years at [[Gustavus Adolphus College]] in Minnesota.<ref name= figuring>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/15/theater/figuring-out-how-to-feel-like-a-man-with-mamet.html |title=Figuring Out How to Feel Like a Man With Mamet |first=Dinitia |last=Smith |authorlink=Dinitia Smith |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 15, 1996}}</ref><ref name= Elmhurst /> He performed for two years in [[Chicago]]'s [[the Second City|Second City]] improvisation group after studying there, and he also helped found [[Victory Gardens Theater]] in Chicago,<ref name= Elmhurst /> investing $1,000.{{citation needed|date= March 2017}}\n\nAfter Second City, he starred in the Organic Theater's 1974 production of [[David Mamet]]'s ''[[Sexual Perversity in Chicago]]'', which established the playwright's characteristic blend of earthy, sometimes brutal dialogue.<ref name= figuring />\n\nHe began appearing on television and films in 1977, making his film debut in 1978 in ''[[An Unmarried Woman]]'', directed by [[Paul Mazursky]]. The following year, he had a small part in [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Manhattan (film)|Manhattan]]''.\n\nHe played a [[terrorist]] in the 1983 television film ''[[Special Bulletin]]''. He appeared on the ''[[Miami Vice]]'' episode \"Bushido\" (first aired November 22, 1985) as a [[KGB]] agent attempting to capture a former colleague of Lt. Castillo ([[Edward James Olmos]]). During his subsequent starring role on ''[[Sledge Hammer!]]'' his character often made jokes about ''Miami Vice''.\n\nRasche played [[Petruchio]] to [[Frances Conroy]]'s Kate in a production of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare's]] ''[[Taming of the Shrew]]'' directed by [[Zoe Caldwell]] at the [[American Shakespeare Theatre]] in [[Stratford, Connecticut]] in the mid-1980s.\n\n===''Sledge Hammer!''===\nRasche is best known for his portrayal of the title character in the satirical television sitcom ''[[Sledge Hammer!]]'', which ran from 1986 to 1988. The show was a spoof of police dramas and concerned the character Sledge Hammer, a violent and chauvinistic police inspector with a taste for large and powerful weaponry.\n\n===Later work===\nRasche had a minor role as a photographer in the movie ''[[Cobra (1986 film)|Cobra]]'' alongside [[Brigitte Nielsen]].\n\nShortly after ''Sledge Hammer!'' ended, he played to critical acclaim in the Broadway production of Mamet's ''[[Speed-the-Plow]]'', and he later appeared in an Off-Broadway revival of Mamet's ''[[Edmond (play)|Edmond]]''.\n\nRasche was lead character Buddy Wheeler in the 1990 Biker Comedy [[Masters of Menace]].\n\nHe played Parnelli, one of two corrupt narcotics police officers, in the 1990 Tom Selleck crime drama, \u201cAn Innocent Man\u201d\n\nRasche played the role of [[Ted Forstmann]] in the 1993 made-for-television movie ''[[Barbarians at the Gate (film)|Barbarians at the Gate]]'', about the [[leveraged buyout]] (LBO) of [[RJR Nabisco]].\n\nRasche had a leading role in the 1997 Columbo episode,  \"A Trace of Murder.\"\n\nIn addition to his work as a screen actor, Rasche can also be heard as [[List of Star Wars characters#P|Captain Piett]] in the [[NPR]] radio adaptation of ''[[Star Wars (radio)#The Empire Strikes Back|The Empire Strikes Back]]''.\n\nHe portrayed Donald Greene, one of the passengers of [[United Airlines Flight 93]], in [[Paul Greengrass]]' 2006 [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] film ''[[United 93 (film)|United 93]]''.\n\nHe had a major role in the 2009 satirical political comedy ''[[In the Loop]]'', as a US official pushing for an invasion of an unspecified [[Middle East]]ern country.\n\nStarting February 14, 2017 he played George Antrobus in [[Theatre for a New Audience]]'s production of [[Thornton Wilder]]'s ''[[The Skin of Our Teeth]]'', opposite [[Kecia Lewis]] as Maggie Antrobus.<ref name= \"TFANA\">{{cite news |last=Clement |first=Olivia |url= http://www.playbill.com/article/the-skin-of-our-teeth-with-kecia-lewis-begins-at-tfna |title=The Skin of Our Teeth, with Kecia Lewis, Begins at TFANA |work=[[Playbill]] |date=2017-02-14 |accessdate=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRasche met his future wife Heather Lupton after he moved to New York City in 1976.<ref name= figuring /> She has taught acting at [[University of California, Santa Barbara]].<ref name= figuring /> Lupton made a guest appearance in the series ''Sledge Hammer'' as Hammer's ex-wife.<ref name= Elmhurst /> They have three children.<ref name= figuring />\n\n==Filmography==\n===Features===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1978 || ''[[An Unmarried Woman]]'' || Performer || uncredited\n|-\n|1979 || ''[[Manhattan (1979 film)|Manhattan]]'' || Television Actor #3 ||\n|-\n| 1979 || ''[[Something Short of Paradise]]'' || David Ritchie ||\n|-\n| 1980 || ''[[Just Tell Me What You Want]]'' || Stopwatch Producer || \n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[Honky Tonk Freeway]]'' || Eddie White || \n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[Fighting Back (1982 American film)|Fighting Back]]'' || Michael Taylor || \n|-\n| 1984 || ''[[Best Defense]]'' || Jeff the 'KBG' Agent || \n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Cobra (1986 film)|Cobra]]'' || Dan || \n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Native Son (1986 film)|Native Son]]'' || Buckley || \n|-\n| 1987 || ''[[Made in Heaven (1987 film)|Made in Heaven]]'' || Donald Sumner || \n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[Wicked Stepmother]]'' || Steve Fisher ||\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[An Innocent Man (film)|An Innocent Man]]'' || Det. Mike Parnell || \n|- \n| 1989 || ''Wedding Band'' || Sloane Vaughn ||\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Masters of Menace]]'' || Buddy Wheeler ||\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Delirious (1991 film)|Delirious]]'' || Dr. Paul Kirkwood/Dennis ||\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Bingo (1991 film)|Bingo]]'' || Hal Devlin || \n|-\n| 1993 || ''[[Twenty Bucks]]'' || Baker || \n|-\n| 1994 || ''[[A Million to Juan]]'' || Jeff || \n|-\n| 1994 || ''[[Bigfoot: The Unforgettable Encounter]]'' || Chaz Frederick || \n